<div id="introduction-what-the-yonezawa-2000-model-does" class="section level2" number="1">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">1</span> Introduction: What the
Yonezawa (2000) model does</h2>
<p><strong>Purpose.</strong> Yonezawa et al. (2000) derive a
<strong>variance effective population size</strong> for
<strong>stage‑structured</strong> populations, where individuals can
<strong>progress or regress</strong> among life‑history stages and
reproduce <strong>sexually and/or clonally</strong>. The framework
connects <strong>demographic transitions</strong> and
<strong>stage‑specific reproduction</strong> to <strong>genetic
drift</strong> by expressing the variance of allele‑frequency change
over one <strong>year</strong> and over one <strong>generation</strong>.
From these, we obtain two effective sizes:</p>
<ul>
<li><span class="math inline">\(N_y\)</span>: <strong>annual</strong>
effective size — drift per <strong>year</strong>;<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(N_e\)</span>:
<strong>generation‑time</strong> effective size — drift over a
<strong>full generation</strong>. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="notation-for-s-stages" class="section level3" number="1.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.1</span> Notation (for <span class="math inline">\(s\)</span> stages)</h3>
<ul>
<li><span class="math inline">\(u_{ji}\)</span>: <strong>transition
rate</strong> (probability a stage‑<span class="math inline">\(i\)</span> plant at <span class="math inline">\(t\)</span> becomes stage <span class="math inline">\(j\)</span> at <span class="math inline">\(t{+}1\)</span>); <span class="math inline">\(u_{\cdot i}\equiv\sum_j u_{ji}\)</span>.<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(\mathbf D=(D_1,\dots,D_s)\)</span>:
<strong>stage fractions</strong> (observed or equilibrium), <span class="math inline">\(\sum_i D_i=1\)</span>.<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(F_i\)</span>: <strong>newborns per
plant</strong> (recruits into the juvenile stage).<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(d_i\in[0,1]\)</span>: <strong>clonal
reproduction rate</strong> of stage <span class="math inline">\(i\)</span>; sexual rate <span class="math inline">\(=1-d_i\)</span>.<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(\left(\dfrac{V_k}{\bar
k}\right)_i\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(\left(\dfrac{V_c}{\bar
c}\right)_i\)</span>: stage‑specific <strong>variance/mean</strong> of
sexual (gametic) and clonal outputs.<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(\bar u_{\cdot}\equiv\sum_i D_i\,u_{\cdot
i}\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(\overline{u^2}\equiv\sum_i
D_i\,u_{\cdot i}^2\)</span>.<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(r_i\equiv F_i D_i\)</span>:
<strong>contribution of newborns</strong> from stage <span class="math inline">\(i\)</span> (recruitment weight).<br />
</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(a\)</span>: <strong>Hardy–Weinberg
deviation</strong> (<span class="math inline">\(a=0\)</span> under
random mating; <span class="math inline">\(a&gt;0\)</span> indicates
excess homozygotes). <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="oneyear-variance-of-allelefrequency-change" class="section level3" number="1.2">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.2</span> One‑year variance of
allele‑frequency change</h3>
<p>Let <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> be the allele frequency
and <span class="math inline">\(pq=p(1-p)\)</span>. Aggregating
survivors/movers and newborns across stages, Yonezawa shows that (at
equilibrium with common <span class="math inline">\(pq\)</span> and
<span class="math inline">\(a\)</span> across stages) the
<strong>one‑year variance</strong> is <span class="math display">\[
V(\Delta p)
= pq\Big\{(1+a)\big(\overline{u^2}-\bar u_{\cdot}^{\,2}\big)
\;+\; (1-\bar
u_{\cdot})\big[\mathrm{Avr}(S)+\mathrm{Avr}(A_d)\big]\Big\},
\]</span> where the newborn‑weighted averages are <span class="math display">\[
\mathrm{Avr}(S)\equiv\frac{\sum_i r_i\,S_i}{\sum_i r_i},
\quad
S_i\equiv (1-a)+(1+a)\left(\frac{V_k}{\bar k}\right)_i,
\]</span> <span class="math display">\[
\mathrm{Avr}(A_d)\equiv\frac{\sum_i r_i\,A_i d_i}{\sum_i r_i},
\quad
A_i\equiv 2(1+a)\left(\frac{V_c}{\bar c}\right)_i - 2S_i.
\]</span> The first term captures variance from
<strong>survival/movement</strong> among stages; the second captures
variance entering via <strong>recruitment</strong> (sexual + clonal),
weighted by how much each stage <strong>supplies newborns</strong>. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
</div>
<div id="generationtime-effective-size-n_e" class="section level3" number="1.3">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.3</span> Generation‑time
effective size <span class="math inline">\(N_e\)</span></h3>
<p>Over one generation of length <span class="math inline">\(L\)</span>,
the total variance of allele‑frequency change is <span class="math inline">\(L\,V(\Delta p)\)</span>. Equating to the
Wright–Fisher expression <span class="math inline">\(pq/(2N_e)\)</span>
gives <span class="math display">\[
\boxed{\,N_e \;=\; \frac{N}{V\,L}\,,\qquad
V \equiv 2(1+a)\big(\overline{u^2}-\bar u_{\cdot}^{\,2}\big)
\;+\; 2(1-\bar u_{\cdot})\big[\mathrm{Avr}(S)+\mathrm{Avr}(A_d)\big]\,}
\]</span> with <span class="math inline">\(N\)</span> the census size at
demographic equilibrium. (Yonezawa also provides growth‑rate corrections
for non‑stationary populations; we focus on the stationary case used to
reproduce Table 4.) <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
<p><strong>Clonal‑dominant, Poisson special case.</strong> When
reproduction is effectively <strong>clonal</strong> with
<strong>Poisson</strong> variance, <span class="math inline">\(a=0\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(\left(\tfrac{V_c}{\bar c}\right)_i=1\)</span>,
yielding the compact expression used in the Fritillaria application:
<span class="math display">\[
\boxed{\,N_e \;\approx\; \frac{N}{\bigl(1-\bar u_{\cdot}\bigr)\,L}\,}
\qquad\text{(paper Eq. 10).}
\]</span> This is the expression behind the <span class="math inline">\(N_e/N\)</span> ratios reported in Table 4 under
the observed low seedling recruitment. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
</div>
<div id="annual-effective-size-n_y" class="section level3" number="1.4">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.4</span> Annual effective size
<span class="math inline">\(N_y\)</span></h3>
<p>For <strong>year‑by‑year</strong> drift (useful in conservation
planning), Yonezawa defines <span class="math display">\[
\boxed{\,N_y \;=\; \frac{N}{1-\bar u_{\cdot}}\,}
\qquad\text{(paper Eq. 11).}
\]</span> As annual survival <span class="math inline">\(\bar
u_{\cdot}\!\to\!1\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(N_y\)</span>
grows, meaning <strong>less drift per year</strong>. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
</div>
<div id="generation-time-l-agebystage-definition" class="section level3" number="1.5">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.5</span> Generation time <span class="math inline">\(L\)</span> (age‑by‑stage definition)</h3>
<p>Let <span class="math inline">\(u_{j\mid x}\)</span> be the
probability that a <strong>newborn</strong> is in stage <span class="math inline">\(j\)</span> at <strong>age <span class="math inline">\(x\)</span></strong> (from matrix powers of <span class="math inline">\([u_{ji}]\)</span>), and let <span class="math inline">\(m_x\)</span> be the mean number of offspring
produced at age <span class="math inline">\(x\)</span> (summing sexual
and clonal across stages). Then <span class="math display">\[
L \;=\; \frac{\sum_x x\,m_x\,\ell_x}{\sum_x m_x\,\ell_x},
\qquad
\ell_x\equiv\sum_j u_{j\mid x},
\qquad
m_x\equiv\sum_j F_j\,u_{j\mid x},
\]</span> with <span class="math inline">\(x\)</span> large enough for
numerical stability (the paper uses <span class="math inline">\(x=1,\dots,500\)</span>). In matrix terms, <span class="math inline">\(u_{j\mid x}\)</span> is the <span class="math inline">\((j,1)\)</span> entry of <span class="math inline">\([u_{ji}]^x\)</span>. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Take‑home.</strong> Demography <span class="math inline">\((u_{ji},F_i,D_i)\)</span> is converted into a
<strong>drift scale</strong> via <span class="math inline">\(V(\Delta
p)\)</span>; then <span class="math inline">\(N_y/N\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(N_e/N\)</span> become concise summaries of drift
risk that incorporate stage structure, survival, and
reproduction—exactly what Yonezawa (2000) reports in
<strong>Table 4</strong>. <a href="https://sistemaupr-my.sharepoint.com/personal/raymond_tremblay_upr_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/NeStage_Yonezawa_Table4.html">1</a></p>
</blockquote>
</div>
</div>
<div id="overview" class="section level2" number="2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">2</span> Overview</h2>
<p>This vignette demonstrates how to compute generation time (L), Ny/N,
and Ne/N using the <strong>exact Yonezawa (2000)</strong> definitions as
implemented in NeStage’s <code>&quot;paper_v1&quot;</code> backend. We:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Reproduce <strong>Table 4</strong> results for the
<strong>Mizuyajiri (Miz)</strong> and <strong>Nanryu (Nan)</strong>
populations using <strong>observed</strong> and
<strong>expected</strong> stage fractions.</p></li>
<li><p>Show a simple <strong>sex-only</strong> example
(illustrative).</p></li>
<li><p>Provide guidance for running the exact backend on <strong>your
own U, F, D</strong> inputs (with optional L computation).</p></li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>Important: To reproduce Yonezawa Table 4 exactly, we use
<code>meta$estimator = &quot;paper_v1&quot;</code> and the paper’s stage fractions
(D) and L values. For new datasets, you can compute L internally by the
paper’s age-by-stage definition when <code>L</code> is not provided.</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
<div id="loading-nestage" class="section level2" number="3">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">3</span> Loading NeStage</h2>
<p>If you have installed the package, simply:</p>
<p>For development (sourcing from <code>R/</code> files), use:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="do">###############################################################################</span></span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># NeStage — Raw replication of Yonezawa et al. (2000) Table 2 and Table 4</span></span>
<span id="cb1-3"><a href="#cb1-3" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Author: Raymond L. Tremblay</span></span>
<span id="cb1-4"><a href="#cb1-4" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Description:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-5"><a href="#cb1-5" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   - Hard-coded data for two populations (Miz, Nan) of Fritillaria camtschatcensis</span></span>
<span id="cb1-6"><a href="#cb1-6" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   - Exact reproduction of Table 2 (transition matrix, stage fractions, survival,</span></span>
<span id="cb1-7"><a href="#cb1-7" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#     newborns per plant, contributions of newborns) and Table 4 (L, Ny/N, Ne/N,</span></span>
<span id="cb1-8"><a href="#cb1-8" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#     minimum N for Ne = 5000, average heterozygosity)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-9"><a href="#cb1-9" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   - Clear explanations of variables for beginners</span></span>
<span id="cb1-10"><a href="#cb1-10" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#</span></span>
<span id="cb1-11"><a href="#cb1-11" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Source for all numbers and variable definitions: Yonezawa et al. 2000, Evolution</span></span>
<span id="cb1-12"><a href="#cb1-12" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   &quot;FORMULATION AND ESTIMATION OF THE EFFECTIVE SIZE OF STAGE-STRUCTURED</span></span>
<span id="cb1-13"><a href="#cb1-13" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#    POPULATIONS IN FRITILLARIA CAMTSCHATCENSIS&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb1-14"><a href="#cb1-14" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   Tables 2 and 4.  (Open-access PDF used for transcription.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-15"><a href="#cb1-15" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   (Please see package References for the OA link.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-16"><a href="#cb1-16" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#   Citation for numeric values: Table 2 &amp; Table 4.  (OA PDF)  [CITE]</span></span>
<span id="cb1-17"><a href="#cb1-17" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="do">###############################################################################</span></span>
<span id="cb1-18"><a href="#cb1-18" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-19"><a href="#cb1-19" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">NeStage — Raw replication of Yonezawa (2000) Table 2 and Table 4</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-20"><a href="#cb1-20" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-21"><a href="#cb1-21" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; NeStage — Raw replication of Yonezawa (2000) Table 2 and Table 4</span></span>
<span id="cb1-22"><a href="#cb1-22" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-23"><a href="#cb1-23" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># -----------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-24"><a href="#cb1-24" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># 1) Stage naming (3 stages)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-25"><a href="#cb1-25" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># -----------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-26"><a href="#cb1-26" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Stage 1: one-leaf, nonflowering</span></span>
<span id="cb1-27"><a href="#cb1-27" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Stage 2: multileaf, nonflowering</span></span>
<span id="cb1-28"><a href="#cb1-28" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Stage 3: multileaf, flowering</span></span>
<span id="cb1-29"><a href="#cb1-29" tabindex="-1"></a>stages <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;one_leaf_nonfl&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;multileaf_nonfl&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;multileaf_flower&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-30"><a href="#cb1-30" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-31"><a href="#cb1-31" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># -----------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-32"><a href="#cb1-32" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># 2) TABLE 2 — Hard-coded data</span></span>
<span id="cb1-33"><a href="#cb1-33" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># -----------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-34"><a href="#cb1-34" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># </span><span class="al">NOTE</span><span class="co">: All values below are transcribed directly from Table 2 (Miz &amp; Nan).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-35"><a href="#cb1-35" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#       Transition matrices are 3x3 with entries u_ji (row j, column i).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-36"><a href="#cb1-36" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#       Survival u·i are the total annual survival rates for stage i.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-37"><a href="#cb1-37" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#       F_i are &quot;newborns per plant&quot; (sexual + clonal recruitment to Stage 1).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-38"><a href="#cb1-38" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#       r_i are contributions of newborns to the whole population.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-39"><a href="#cb1-39" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#       S r_i is the recruitment rate (sums of r_i).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-40"><a href="#cb1-40" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#</span></span>
<span id="cb1-41"><a href="#cb1-41" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># SOURCE: Yonezawa et al. 2000, Evolution, Table 2.  [CITE]</span></span>
<span id="cb1-42"><a href="#cb1-42" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-43"><a href="#cb1-43" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># --- Population Miz (Table 2) -----------------------------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-44"><a href="#cb1-44" tabindex="-1"></a>T_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">matrix</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(</span>
<span id="cb1-45"><a href="#cb1-45" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.789</span>, <span class="fl">0.121</span>, <span class="fl">0.054</span>,</span>
<span id="cb1-46"><a href="#cb1-46" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.007</span>, <span class="fl">0.621</span>, <span class="fl">0.335</span>,</span>
<span id="cb1-47"><a href="#cb1-47" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.001</span>, <span class="fl">0.258</span>, <span class="fl">0.611</span></span>
<span id="cb1-48"><a href="#cb1-48" tabindex="-1"></a>), <span class="at">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">byrow =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>, <span class="at">dimnames =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(stages, stages))  <span class="co"># u_ji</span></span>
<span id="cb1-49"><a href="#cb1-49" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-50"><a href="#cb1-50" tabindex="-1"></a>D_obs_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.935</span>, <span class="fl">0.038</span>, <span class="fl">0.027</span>)   <span class="co"># observed fractions (D1, D2, D3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-51"><a href="#cb1-51" tabindex="-1"></a>D_exp_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.921</span>, <span class="fl">0.046</span>, <span class="fl">0.033</span>)   <span class="co"># expected fractions (equilibrium solution)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-52"><a href="#cb1-52" tabindex="-1"></a>u_surv_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.797</span>, <span class="fl">1.000</span>, <span class="fl">1.000</span>)  <span class="co"># (u·1, u·2, u·3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-53"><a href="#cb1-53" tabindex="-1"></a>F_vec_Miz  <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.055</span>, <span class="fl">1.328</span>, <span class="fl">2.398</span>)  <span class="co"># newborns per plant (F1, F2, F3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-54"><a href="#cb1-54" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-55"><a href="#cb1-55" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Standard “fecundity matrix” form (recruitment to Stage 1):</span></span>
<span id="cb1-56"><a href="#cb1-56" tabindex="-1"></a>F_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">matrix</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="at">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">dimnames =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(stages, stages))</span>
<span id="cb1-57"><a href="#cb1-57" tabindex="-1"></a>F_Miz[<span class="dv">1</span>, ] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> F_vec_Miz</span>
<span id="cb1-58"><a href="#cb1-58" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-59"><a href="#cb1-59" tabindex="-1"></a>r_vec_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.051</span>, <span class="fl">0.050</span>, <span class="fl">0.065</span>)   <span class="co"># contributions of newborns (r1, r2, r3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-60"><a href="#cb1-60" tabindex="-1"></a>r_sum_Miz <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(r_vec_Miz)           <span class="co"># = 0.166</span></span>
<span id="cb1-61"><a href="#cb1-61" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-62"><a href="#cb1-62" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># --- Population Nan (Table 2) -----------------------------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-63"><a href="#cb1-63" tabindex="-1"></a>T_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">matrix</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(</span>
<span id="cb1-64"><a href="#cb1-64" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.748</span>, <span class="fl">0.137</span>, <span class="fl">0.138</span>,</span>
<span id="cb1-65"><a href="#cb1-65" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.006</span>, <span class="fl">0.669</span>, <span class="fl">0.374</span>,</span>
<span id="cb1-66"><a href="#cb1-66" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fl">0.001</span>, <span class="fl">0.194</span>, <span class="fl">0.488</span></span>
<span id="cb1-67"><a href="#cb1-67" tabindex="-1"></a>), <span class="at">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">byrow =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>, <span class="at">dimnames =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(stages, stages))  <span class="co"># u_ji</span></span>
<span id="cb1-68"><a href="#cb1-68" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-69"><a href="#cb1-69" tabindex="-1"></a>D_obs_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.958</span>, <span class="fl">0.027</span>, <span class="fl">0.015</span>)   <span class="co"># observed fractions (D1, D2, D3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-70"><a href="#cb1-70" tabindex="-1"></a>D_exp_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.951</span>, <span class="fl">0.034</span>, <span class="fl">0.015</span>)   <span class="co"># expected fractions</span></span>
<span id="cb1-71"><a href="#cb1-71" tabindex="-1"></a>u_surv_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.755</span>, <span class="fl">1.000</span>, <span class="fl">1.000</span>)  <span class="co"># (u·1, u·2, u·3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-72"><a href="#cb1-72" tabindex="-1"></a>F_vec_Nan  <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.138</span>, <span class="fl">2.773</span>, <span class="fl">5.016</span>)  <span class="co"># newborns per plant (F1, F2, F3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-73"><a href="#cb1-73" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-74"><a href="#cb1-74" tabindex="-1"></a>F_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">matrix</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="at">nrow =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">ncol =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">dimnames =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(stages, stages))</span>
<span id="cb1-75"><a href="#cb1-75" tabindex="-1"></a>F_Nan[<span class="dv">1</span>, ] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> F_vec_Nan</span>
<span id="cb1-76"><a href="#cb1-76" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-77"><a href="#cb1-77" tabindex="-1"></a>r_vec_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fl">0.132</span>, <span class="fl">0.075</span>, <span class="fl">0.075</span>)   <span class="co"># contributions of newborns (r1, r2, r3)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-78"><a href="#cb1-78" tabindex="-1"></a>r_sum_Nan <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(r_vec_Nan)           <span class="co"># = 0.282</span></span>
<span id="cb1-79"><a href="#cb1-79" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-80"><a href="#cb1-80" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Pack both populations (Option B)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-81"><a href="#cb1-81" tabindex="-1"></a>yonezawa_table2 <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(</span>
<span id="cb1-82"><a href="#cb1-82" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="at">Miz =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(</span>
<span id="cb1-83"><a href="#cb1-83" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">stages =</span> stages,</span>
<span id="cb1-84"><a href="#cb1-84" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">T =</span> T_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-85"><a href="#cb1-85" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">F =</span> F_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-86"><a href="#cb1-86" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">Fvec =</span> F_vec_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-87"><a href="#cb1-87" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">D_observed =</span> D_obs_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-88"><a href="#cb1-88" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">D_expected =</span> D_exp_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-89"><a href="#cb1-89" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">u_survival =</span> u_surv_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-90"><a href="#cb1-90" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">r =</span> r_vec_Miz,</span>
<span id="cb1-91"><a href="#cb1-91" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">recruitment_rate =</span> r_sum_Miz</span>
<span id="cb1-92"><a href="#cb1-92" tabindex="-1"></a>  ),</span>
<span id="cb1-93"><a href="#cb1-93" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="at">Nan =</span> <span class="fu">list</span>(</span>
<span id="cb1-94"><a href="#cb1-94" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">stages =</span> stages,</span>
<span id="cb1-95"><a href="#cb1-95" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">T =</span> T_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-96"><a href="#cb1-96" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">F =</span> F_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-97"><a href="#cb1-97" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">Fvec =</span> F_vec_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-98"><a href="#cb1-98" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">D_observed =</span> D_obs_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-99"><a href="#cb1-99" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">D_expected =</span> D_exp_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-100"><a href="#cb1-100" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">u_survival =</span> u_surv_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-101"><a href="#cb1-101" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">r =</span> r_vec_Nan,</span>
<span id="cb1-102"><a href="#cb1-102" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">recruitment_rate =</span> r_sum_Nan</span>
<span id="cb1-103"><a href="#cb1-103" tabindex="-1"></a>  )</span>
<span id="cb1-104"><a href="#cb1-104" tabindex="-1"></a>)</span>
<span id="cb1-105"><a href="#cb1-105" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-106"><a href="#cb1-106" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Pretty-print function for Table 2</span></span>
<span id="cb1-107"><a href="#cb1-107" tabindex="-1"></a>print_table2 <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(obj, pop_label) {</span>
<span id="cb1-108"><a href="#cb1-108" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">==================== Table 2 —&quot;</span>, pop_label, <span class="st">&quot;====================</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-109"><a href="#cb1-109" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Stage order: &quot;</span>, <span class="fu">paste</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>stages, <span class="at">collapse =</span> <span class="st">&quot;, &quot;</span>), <span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>, <span class="at">sep =</span> <span class="st">&quot;&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-110"><a href="#cb1-110" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Transition matrix u_ji (rows = recipient stage j, cols = source stage i):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-111"><a href="#cb1-111" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>T, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-112"><a href="#cb1-112" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Stage fractions D (observed):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>D_observed, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-113"><a href="#cb1-113" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Stage fractions D (expected at equilibrium):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>D_expected, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-114"><a href="#cb1-114" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Survival rates u·i (per stage):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>u_survival, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-115"><a href="#cb1-115" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Newborns per plant F_i (recruitment to stage 1):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>Fvec, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-116"><a href="#cb1-116" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Fecundity matrix F (row 1 = F_i, others 0):</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>F, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-117"><a href="#cb1-117" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Contributions of newborns r_i:</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>); <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>r, <span class="dv">3</span>))</span>
<span id="cb1-118"><a href="#cb1-118" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Recruitment rate sum(r_i): &quot;</span>, <span class="fu">round</span>(obj<span class="sc">$</span>recruitment_rate, <span class="dv">3</span>), <span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>, <span class="at">sep =</span> <span class="st">&quot;&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-119"><a href="#cb1-119" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">invisible</span>(<span class="cn">NULL</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-120"><a href="#cb1-120" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb1-121"><a href="#cb1-121" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-122"><a href="#cb1-122" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Print both populations (Table 2)</span></span>
