<span id="cb1-281"><a href="#cb1-281" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; -----------------------------------------------------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-282"><a href="#cb1-282" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Glossary (beginner-friendly)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-283"><a href="#cb1-283" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; -----------------------------------------------------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-284"><a href="#cb1-284" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; stages:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-285"><a href="#cb1-285" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Ordered vector of life-history stages used throughout (3 stages here).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-286"><a href="#cb1-286" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   1 = one-leaf, nonflowering; 2 = multileaf, nonflowering; 3 = multileaf, flowering.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-287"><a href="#cb1-287" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-288"><a href="#cb1-288" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; T (transition matrix u_ji):</span></span>
<span id="cb1-289"><a href="#cb1-289" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   3x3 matrix; entry (j,i) is the probability that a plant in stage i at</span></span>
<span id="cb1-290"><a href="#cb1-290" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   year t will be in stage j at year t+1 (including staying in the same</span></span>
<span id="cb1-291"><a href="#cb1-291" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   stage, moving up, or moving down). Rows sum &lt;= 1; columns describe</span></span>
<span id="cb1-292"><a href="#cb1-292" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   fates of each source stage. (Table 2.)  [Yonezawa 2000]</span></span>
<span id="cb1-293"><a href="#cb1-293" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-294"><a href="#cb1-294" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; D_observed, D_expected:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-295"><a href="#cb1-295" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Fractions of the population in each stage (observed vs equilibrium).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-296"><a href="#cb1-296" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Expected values come from the equilibrium of the projection system.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-297"><a href="#cb1-297" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-298"><a href="#cb1-298" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; u_survival (u·i):</span></span>
<span id="cb1-299"><a href="#cb1-299" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Annual survival probabilities by stage (Table 2): probability that an</span></span>
<span id="cb1-300"><a href="#cb1-300" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   individual in stage i survives (to any stage) to the next year.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-301"><a href="#cb1-301" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-302"><a href="#cb1-302" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Fvec (F_i):</span></span>
<span id="cb1-303"><a href="#cb1-303" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Newborns per plant for each stage (Table 2). In this model, newborns</span></span>
<span id="cb1-304"><a href="#cb1-304" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   recruit to Stage 1. We also provide F as a 3x3 matrix with row 1 = F_i.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-305"><a href="#cb1-305" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-306"><a href="#cb1-306" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; r (r_i) and recruitment_rate:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-307"><a href="#cb1-307" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   r_i are the contributions of newborns to the whole population from</span></span>
<span id="cb1-308"><a href="#cb1-308" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   parents in stage i in that year; sum(r_i) is the total recruitment rate.</span></span>
<span id="cb1-309"><a href="#cb1-309" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-310"><a href="#cb1-310" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; L (generation time):</span></span>
<span id="cb1-311"><a href="#cb1-311" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Average generation length consistent with the stage-structured model</span></span>
<span id="cb1-312"><a href="#cb1-312" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   used in the paper. (Reported in Table 4.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-313"><a href="#cb1-313" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-314"><a href="#cb1-314" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Ny_over_N:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-315"><a href="#cb1-315" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   &quot;Annual&quot; effective population size measured per year (Ny) relative to the</span></span>
<span id="cb1-316"><a href="#cb1-316" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   census size N. Larger Ny/N implies less genetic drift per year. (Table 4.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-317"><a href="#cb1-317" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-318"><a href="#cb1-318" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Ne_over_N:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-319"><a href="#cb1-319" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   &quot;Generation-time&quot; effective population size (Ne) relative to N—captures</span></span>
<span id="cb1-320"><a href="#cb1-320" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   drift across a full generation. (Table 4.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-321"><a href="#cb1-321" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-322"><a href="#cb1-322" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Min_N_for_Ne5000:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-323"><a href="#cb1-323" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Minimum census size required to achieve Ne = 5000, given the observed</span></span>
<span id="cb1-324"><a href="#cb1-324" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Ne/N ratio (Table 4).</span></span>
<span id="cb1-325"><a href="#cb1-325" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-326"><a href="#cb1-326" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; H_mean, H_sd:</span></span>
<span id="cb1-327"><a href="#cb1-327" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;   Average heterozygosity (± SD) across assayed loci. (Table 4.)</span></span>
<span id="cb1-328"><a href="#cb1-328" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; -----------------------------------------------------------------------</span></span>
<span id="cb1-329"><a href="#cb1-329" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb1-330"><a href="#cb1-330" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">cat</span>(<span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">Done. This file reproduces Table 2 and Table 4 as printed in the paper.</span><span class="sc">\n</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-331"><a href="#cb1-331" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; </span></span>
<span id="cb1-332"><a href="#cb1-332" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; Done. This file reproduces Table 2 and Table 4 as printed in the paper.</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="reproducing-yonezawa-2000-table-4" class="section level2" number="4">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4</span> Reproducing Yonezawa
(2000) Table 4</h2>
<p>We use helper inputs for Miz/Nan (U, F, D_obs, D_exp, L) and call
<code>nestage_exact()</code> with the exact backend.</p>
<p>You should see values that match Table 4 (rounded):</p>
<ul>
<li></li>
<li><p>Miz: L = <strong>13.399</strong>, Ny/N = <strong>2.932
(2.976)</strong>, Ne/N = <strong>0.219 (0.222)</strong></p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p>Nan: L = <strong>8.353</strong>, Ny/N = <strong>2.428
(2.446)</strong>, Ne/N = <strong>0.291 (0.293)</strong></p></li>
<li></li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>Note on rounding: Formatting in the original table may reflect
rounding at the third decimal. Small differences (±0.001–0.002) are
expected depending on rounding conventions.</p>
</blockquote>
<div id="quick-point-only-plot-no-bars" class="section level3" number="4.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">4.1</span> Quick point-only plot
(no bars)</h3>
<p>We can visualize Ny/N and Ne/N for the four results (Miz/Nan and
their parenthetical values) using <strong>points</strong> (not bars). If
<code>ggplot2</code> is available we use it; otherwise base plots.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="sex-only-example-illustrative" class="section level2" number="5">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5</span> Sex-only example
(illustrative)</h2>
<p>This shows how to run a <strong>sex-only</strong> variant by scaling
fecundity for a given stage while keeping the exact backend. Here we
reduce stage-3 reproduction to 10% of the original for Miz, and we keep
the observed stage fractions D_obs for reporting.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Caution: Under extreme down-scaling of fecundity,
<code>1 - overline(u^2)</code> can become very small, and <code>L</code>
may increase, which can yield large Ny/N and Ne/N. These are
mathematically consistent with the formulation but should be interpreted
with care.</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
<div id="using-your-own-u-f-d-and-l" class="section level2" number="6">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">6</span> Using your own U, F, D
(and L)</h2>
<p>For a general dataset:</p>
<ul>
<li></li>
<li><p>Provide <code>U</code> (square transition matrix) and
<code>F</code> (length k fecundity vector).</p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p>Provide stage fractions <code>D</code> (length k, non-negative,
sum to 1) for reporting weights.</p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p>Optionally provide <code>L</code>. If omitted, NeStage will
compute L using the paper’s age-by-stage definition
<code>L(U, F)</code>.</p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p>Force the exact backend via
<code>meta$estimator = &quot;paper_v1&quot;</code>.</p></li>
</ul>
<div id="stage-order-alignment-and-assembly-notes" class="section level3" number="6.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">6.1</span> Stage-order alignment
and assembly notes</h3>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li></li>
<li><p><strong>Stage order</strong> must be consistent across
<code>U</code>, <code>F</code>, and <code>D</code>.</p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p><strong>Lambda reporting</strong> uses
<code>A_full &lt;- U; A_full[1, ] &lt;- F</code> (row 1 is fecundity
only).</p></li>
<li></li>
<li><p>If you only have a full projection matrix <code>A</code> and no
split into <code>U</code> and <code>F</code>, you can heuristically set
<code>F &lt;- A[1, ]</code> and <code>U &lt;- A; U[1, ] &lt;- 0</code>,
but exact replication of Table 4 requires the correct paper
<code>U</code> and <code>F</code>.</p></li>
<li></li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
